      <notesStmt>
        <note rend="IDENTIFICATION">
          <p>Paris, Bibliothèque nationale de France, fr. 801</p>
        </note>
        <note rend="CONTENTS">
          <p><hi rend="italics">Roman de la Rose</hi> (ff. 1r-128v)</p>
        </note>
        <note rend="MATERIAL">
          <p>Parchment</p>
        </note>
        <note rend="ORIGIN">
          <p>France</p>
        </note>
        <note rend="DATE">
          <p>15th century</p>
        </note>
        <note rend="SCRIPT">
          <p>Gothic, written in 2 columns of 40-50 lines, 1 scribe</p>
        </note>
        <note rend="ARTISTS">
          <p>1 artist</p>
        </note>
        <note rend="DECORATION">
          <p>31 single-column panel miniatures in brown ink and colors with red/blue or blue
                  frames (ff. 1r, 1v, 2r (x2), 2v (x2), 3r, 3v (x2), 4v, 5r, 7r, 8r, 8v (x3), 9r,
                  11v (x2), 12r, 13r, 17r (x2), 17v, 18r, 19r (x2), 22v (x2), 23r, 23v). The
                  scribe's instructions for the artist are beside several miniatures. Blue and red
                  pen initials throughout. </p>
        </note>
        <note rend="DIMENSIONS">
          <p>350 x 248 mm (this measurement is from Langlois)</p>
        </note>
        <note rend="FOLIATION">
          <p>ff. vi + 128 + iv</p>
        </note>
        <note rend="BINDING">
          <p>French, early 19th century; brown calf marbled binding with gilt decorative border
                  and arms of Napoleon I stamped in the centre of upper and lower covers, title of
                  the book and initials of Napoleon in gilt on spine, marbled endpapers.</p>
        </note>
        <note rend="PROVENANCE">
          <p> Martel family arms painted three times (ff. <locus>1r</locus>,
                  <locus>21r</locus>, <locus>65r</locus>); in the royal library at Fontainebleau
                  (ms. 630), 16th century; 18th century stamp of Bibliotheca Regiae (royal library),
                  where it was ms. 7196 (ff. <locus>1r</locus>, <locus>128v</locus>)</p>
        </note>
        <note rend="NOTES">
          <p>Fragments of a 12th-century liturgical book serve as flyleaves
                     (<locus>frontmatter.flyleaf.05r</locus> and
                  <locus>endmatter.flyleaf.01r</locus>). On <locus>frontmatter.flyleaf.06v</locus> a
                  dialogue between Macquet or Marquet and a sleeping character was added in the late
                  15th century.</p>
        </note>
        <note rend="SELECT BIBLIOGRAPHY">
          <p>1. Paulin Paris, <hi rend="italics">Les manuscrits françois de la Bibliothèque du
                     roi</hi> (Paris: Techener, 1836-1848), IV, pp. 232-234</p>
          <p>2. Langlois, <hi rend="italics">Les manuscrits</hi>, pp. 8-9 </p>
        </note>
